<b>Blackcurrant seed oil</b> is derived from the seeds of <it><link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../161/172161.xml">
Ribes nigrum</link></it> (blackcurrant, or European currant). It contains an unusually high amount of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../218/681218.xml">
omega-6</link> (15-20 percent) as well as a high amount of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../594/22594.xml">
omega-3</link> fatty acids (12-14 percent). It also contains <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../497/880497.xml">
linoleic acid</link> as well as 2-4 percent <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../140/3956140.xml">
stearidonic acid</link>. There are some indications that black currant seed oil is anti-inflammatory and cardioprotective.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref> In European <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../857/457857.xml">
folk medicine</link>, black currant once had a considerable reputation for controlling <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../951/53951.xml">
diarrhea</link>, promoting urine output (as a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../078/9078.xml">
diuretic</link>) and reducing <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../776/1776.xml">
arthritic</link> and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../499/593499.xml">
rheumatic</link> pains.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref> It is primarily used medicinally and as a diet supplement.
